				By Didi Kirsten Tatlow			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-03-05T07:05:53+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 5, 2014 2:05 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 5, 2014 2:05 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/05/world/05sino-pollution01/05sino-pollution01-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/05/world/05sino-pollution01/05sino-pollution01-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/05/world/05sino-pollution01/05sino-pollution01-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002750575" width="592" height="399" alt="A group of Chinese and foreigners distributed face masks to pedestrians on the Bund in Shanghai in January to raise awareness of air pollution."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="399"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A group of Chinese and foreigners distributed face masks to pedestrians on the Bund in Shanghai in January to raise awareness of air pollution.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Carlos Barria/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/05/china-declares-war-against-pollution/" data-title="China Declares &#8216;War Against Pollution&#8217;" data-description="Facing growing dissatisfaction from citizens about high pollution in China, the premier, Li Keqiang, declared in his work report Wednesday that the government he leads would &quot;declare war&quot; on pollution. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The first year of President Xi Jinping&#8217;s administration, Prime Minister Li Keqiang <a href="//live.china.org.cn/2014/03/04/coming-soon-premier-li-keqiang-delivers-govt-work-report-at-12th-npc-session/">said</a> at the opening of the National People&#8217;s Congress on Wednesday, was: &#8220;Arduous.&#8221; &#8220;Complex.&#8221; &#8220;Difficult.&#8221; &#8220;Downward pressure on the economy increased.&#8221; &#8220;Natural disasters occurred frequently.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After this grim assessment, Mr. Li turned to the good news in his <a href="//news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2014-03/05/c_133162002.htm">annual work report</a>: The economy was stable and improved, with G.D.P. up 7.7 percent over last year to $56.9 trillion renminbi, or $9.2 trillion. Personal incomes rose, up 9.3 percent in real terms for rural residents and 7 percent for urban residents. Social programs â education, science and technology, culture and health â developed &#8220;vigorously,&#8221; he said, and China sent one spacecraft into orbit and landed another on the moon, and a submersible broke the record for manned deep-sea dives.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Chinese are accustomed to this form of presentation: descriptions of struggle, followed by lists of achievements, mostly economic. But then came something new, as Mr. Li addressed an issue, in colorful language, that is increasingly important to many Chinese: pollution.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-7241"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was the last item on a list of nine &#8220;Major Tasks for 2014&#8243;: &#8220;Building China into a beautiful homeland with a sound ecological environment.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The standout phrase: &#8220;We will declare war against pollution and fight it with the same determination we battled poverty.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Smog is affecting larger parts of China, and environmental pollution has become a major problem,&#8221; Mr. Li said, &#8220;which is nature&#8217;s red-light warning against the model of inefficient and blind development.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Air pollution in China regularly reaches hazardous levels and appears to be worsening, with seemingly ever-longer periods of smog affecting larger areas of the country. In recent months, more and more citizens have taken to wearing antipollution masks in public. Pollution is a key reason Chinese cite for emigrating.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among the specifics: Mr. Li said that 50,000 &#8220;small coal-fired furnaces&#8221; would be shut down in 2014. Coal-burning power plants with a production capacity of 15 million kilowatts will undergo &#8220;desulphurization,&#8221; plants with a production capacity of 130 million kilowatts will undergo &#8220;denitrification,&#8221; and plants with a production capacity of 180 million kilowatts will undergo &#8220;dust removal.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Six million older, high-emission motor vehicles will be removed from the roads and high-quality diesel fuel will be provided nationwide, he said. He promised energy conservation measures and &#8220;a sound system of tiered pricing for household water and gas consumption&#8221; to help safeguard resources.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Governments at all levels and the whole society should act more vigorously to protect the land our lives depend on,&#8221; Mr. Li said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After the downbeat opening, the positive figures and the call to arms over pollution, came a rousing, political finale.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Let us rally closely around the Party Central Committee with Comrade Xi Jinping as general secretary, hold high the great banner of socialism with Chinese characteristics and work together as one,&#8221; Mr. Li said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;With all these efforts, we can surely realize the Chinese dream of the great rejuvenation of the Chinese nation!&#8221;</p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
